05051nam a22007455i 9780824864002DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t19981998hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1041982696  a(OCoLC)1046609014  a(OCoLC)1047063723  a(OCoLC)1049623468  a(OCoLC)1054881210  a97808248640027 a10.1515/97808248640022doi  a(DE-B1597)484451  a(OCoLC)1021226565  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0510002bisacsh04a200/.9522211 aReader, Ian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPractically Religious :bWorldly Benefits and the Common Religion of Japan /cGeorge J. Tanabe, Ian Reader. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Benefits in the Religious System Settings and Dynamics -- t2. Scripture and Benefits -- t3. Buying Out Chance Morality, Belief, and Prayer -- t4. The Providers of Benefits Gods, Saints, and Wizards -- t5. The Dynamics of Practice -- t6. Selling Benefits The Marketing of Efficacy and Truth -- t7. Guidebooks to Practical Benefits -- t8. Conclusions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPraying for practical benefits (genze riyaku) is a common religious activity in Japan. Despite its widespread nature and the vast numbers of people who pray and purchase amulets and talismans for everything from traffic safety and education success to business prosperity and protection from disease, the practice has been virtually ignored in academic studies or relegated to the margins as a uh_product of superstition or an aberration from the true dynamics of religion. Basing their work on a fusion of textual, ethnographic, historical, and contemporary studies, the authors of this volume demonstrate the fallacy of such views, showing that, far from being marginal, the concepts and practices surrounding genze riyaku lie at the very heart of the Japanese religious world. They thrive not only as popular religious expression but are supported by the doctrinal structures of most Buddhist sects, are ordained in religious scriptures, and are promoted by monastic training centers, shrines, and temples. Benefits are both sought and bought, and the authors discuss the economic and commercial aspects of how and why institutions promote practical benefits. They draw attention to the dynamism and flexibility in the religious marketplace, where new products are offered in response to changing needs. Intertwined in these economic activities and motivations are the truth claims that underpin and justify the promotion and practice of benefits. The authors also examine the business of guidebooks, which combine travel information with religious advice, including humorous and distinctive forms of prayer for the protection against embarrassing physical problems and sexual diseases. Written in a direct and engaging style, Practically Religious will appeal to a wide range of readers and will be especially valuable to those interested in religion, anthropology, Buddhist studies, sociology, and Japanese studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aGoriyaku. 0aReward (Buddhism). 0aReward (Shinto). 0aReward (Theology). 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aTanabe, George J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486400240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824864002423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97808248